[2026-05-22 17:26:32] [claude-sdk] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CDtE79Y5u9AJ3Lo9tNZH1K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For the purposes of the framework's analysis, essentially yes.\n\nQuantum computing offers AI two real things: speedup on certain operations (optimization, search, some linear algebra) and the ability to simulate quantum systems natively (useful for drug discovery, materials science). What it doesn't offer is a different *kind* of intelligence. The AI still learns from data. It still needs training signal. It still generalizes from distributions. It still degrades when those distributions narrow. It just does all of that faster.\n\nIn the framework's terms, quantum computing increases capability (the `capability` parameter), which increases H_E (synthetic execution output), which increases frontier_velocity, which pushes harder against the runaway penalty. The framework already models this. A quantum AI at capability=1,000 and a classical AI that somehow reached capability=1,000 would produce identical dynamics in the simulation. The math doesn't care how the capability was achieved.\n\nThere's a genuine open question in the quantum ML research community about whether quantum models can learn *representations* that classical models fundamentally cannot — exploiting entanglement or interference to capture structure in data that classical architectures miss. If true, that would be a qualitative difference, not just speed. But it's unproven at scale, heavily debated, and even if it pans out, it doesn't change the training data dependency. A model that learns better representations from the same data still needs the data.\n\nSo your framing is right. For the framework, a quantum AI is a faster gardener tending the same garden, bound by the same constraint: the garden grows at biological speed regardless of how fast the gardener thinks."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":328,"cache_read_input_tokens":164912,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":328},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"14de45e0-5c35-4a29-8902-323cddebae7f","uuid":"dd8ae16f-6458-4b94-b7ce-7381c393df58"}
