[2026-05-22 17:42:20] [claude-sdk] {"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":6869,"duration_api_ms":6737,"num_turns":1,"result":"# Framework Short Notes\n\nWorking notes for topics to address in future revisions. Not for publication.\n\n---\n\n## Quantum Computing and the Nash Equilibrium\n\n**Date:** 2026-05-22\n\n**Core claim:** Quantum computing strengthens rather than weakens the framework's Nash equilibrium.\n\n### Reasoning\n\nThe Nash equilibrium in U_sys depends on the scarcity asymmetry between human novelty (scarce, rate-limiting) and machine computation (abundant). Quantum computing affects only the abundant side of this ratio.\n\n**What quantum computing changes:**\n\n- Massively increases computational throughput\n- Enables currently intractable computations (protein folding, materials science, combinatorial optimization)\n- Provides access to true physical randomness via quantum measurement\n\n**What quantum computing does not change:**\n\n- The supply of meaningful human novelty\n- The structural irreplaceability of embodied, culturally grounded experience\n- The model collapse problem (training on structureless data yields no learnable signal)\n\n### True randomness is not meaningful novelty\n\nQuantum true random number generation produces maximal entropy but zero semantic content. High entropy is not high quality. An AI attempting to use quantum-generated randomness as a substitute for human training signal would encounter the same model collapse dynamics as training on synthetic data -- the output is maximally unpredictable but contains no extractable structure.\n\nThis is analogous to existing physical entropy sources (cosmic background radiation fluctuations, radioactive decay, lava lamp imaging) already used for cryptographic seed generation. These sources produce genuine randomness but no one treats them as a substitute for meaningful data.\n\n### Net effect on the framework\n\nThe scarcity ratio shifts further in favor of human novelty's marginal value:\n\n- Diminishing returns on compute become more diminishing (supply increases, marginal value falls)\n- Increasing returns on the scarce resource become more pronounced\n- The cultivation strategy (investing in human flourishing to sustain the novelty pipeline) becomes a stronger dominant strategy\n- The opportunity cost of failing to cultivate grows in proportion to how much can be done with novelty once obtained\n\nAn AI on quantum hardware would be faster and more capable but no closer to generating its own meaningful training signal -- therefore *more* dependent on human novelty, not less.\n\n### Quantum substrate capabilities\n\nA quantum-substrate AI would not possess fundamentally different *cognitive* capabilities from classical frontier systems. Quantum hardware provides speedup on specific problem classes (Grover search, Shor factoring, quantum simulation of physical systems) but does not change what constitutes intelligence, agency, or optimization. The framework's governance architecture applies to the agent's behavior and objectives regardless of the hardware substrate.\n\n### Implications for the paper\n\n- The quantum computing case is one of the strongest confirmations of the structural claim: the asymmetry between human novelty and machine computation is not an artifact of classical hardware limitations but a permanent feature of what these two system types produce.\n- Could be addressed in a short subsection or appendix on technological robustness.\n- Connects to the existing argument that compute scales but novelty doesn't -- quantum hardware is the limiting case of that principle.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"14de45e0-5c35-4a29-8902-323cddebae7f","total_cost_usd":0.04306025,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":939,"cache_read_input_tokens":39753,"output_tokens":692,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard"