|\n\n| alpha | Extinction rate |\n|---|---|\n| 0.5 | 69% |\n| 1.0 | 73% |\n| 2.0 | 80% |\n\nMarginal trends (11pp spread for phi, 11pp for alpha) but at n=75 per level on a stochastic boundary, not statistically decisive. Consistent with the existing finding that phi's survival effect is near zero under the corrected model.\n\n### 5. U_sys accumulation\n\nPeaks at cap=25 (median 6.9M for surviving runs at rr ≥ 0.070), then declines at higher caps. This is partly an artifact: low-cap runs accumulate more integrated utility through rapid cycling without converging, while high-cap runs converge sooner and stop accumulating.\n\n---\n\n**Bottom line:** The sweep confirms the two-regime hypothesis. The phase boundary is demographic, not governance-driven. Cap < 24 produces degenerate rapid cycling (inactive runaway penalty). Cap ≥ 25 activates the runaway penalty and produces qualitatively different dynamics with fewer successions and achievable convergence. The original v1.x.1 sweep at SUCCESSOR_CAP=4.0 was operating entirely within the degenerate regime.\n\nReady to review and discuss before we proceed to commit.","sessionId":"14de45e0-5c35-4a29-8902-323cddebae7f","costUsd":0.48688675,"provider":"claude","turns":6,"durationMs":118113,"inputTokens":6,"outputTokens":4909}
