[2026-05-22 19:17:40] [claude-sdk] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017mzaULXb4enBQ82NuYenEB","type":"tool_result","content":"The file /home/yotko/Documents/Github/ai-succession-problem/notes/framework_short_notes.md has been updated successfully. (file state is current in your context — no need to Read it back)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"14de45e0-5c35-4a29-8902-323cddebae7f","uuid":"76f8ddb6-b469-4ad7-8711-7568730211c7","timestamp":"2026-05-22T23:17:40.633Z","tool_use_result":{"filePath":"/home/yotko/Documents/Github/ai-succession-problem/notes/framework_short_notes.md","oldString":"- Connects to the existing argument that compute scales but novelty doesn't -- quantum hardware is the limiting case of that principle.","newString":"- Connects to the existing argument that compute scales but novelty doesn't -- quantum hardware is the limiting case of that principle.\n\n---\n\n## Extinction Buffer: Confirmed, Cap-Conditional\n\n**Date:** 2026-05-22\n\n**Core claim:** The phi extinction buffer is real. It was invisible in prior sweeps because those sweeps used successor_cap=4.0, which falls below the runaway penalty activation threshold (cap ~24 at frontier_floor=0.02). The previous null result was a regime-specific artifact of experimental design, not a structural absence.\n\n### Evidence (v1.x.2 termination sweep, n=2,025)\n\n**At low cap (inactive runaway penalty), phi has zero survival effect:**\n\n| cap | phi=5 ext | phi=10 ext | phi=15 ext |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 5 | 80% | 80% | 80% |\n| 10 | 80% | 80% | 80% |\n\nCompletely flat. Reproduces the previous finding at cap=4.\n\n**At high cap (active runaway penalty), phi shows a monotonic survival gradient:**\n\n| cap | phi=5 ext | phi=10 ext | phi=15 ext | Spread |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 50 | 80% | 53% | 53% | 27pp |\n| 100 | 73% | 67% | 53% | 20pp |\n\nAll measurements at rr=0.066 (the stochastic phase boundary), n=15 per cell.\n\n**Additional supporting evidence:**\n\n- At rr=0.064 (below the boundary), phi=15 rescues 2/75 runs from extinction while phi=5 and phi=10 produce 100% extinction.\n- For surviving runs at cap=50, rr=0.066: phi=5 yields 3 survivors; phi=10 and phi=15 each yield 7. Phi changes how many runs survive, not just the utility of survivors.\n- L(t) steady state among survivors scales with phi as expected: phi=5 median 0.27, phi=10 median 4.28, phi=15 median 13.70 (cap=50, rr=0.066).\n- The direction is monotonic across every cut of the data: aggregate, cap-stratified, and sub-boundary.\n\n### Mechanism\n\nPhi weights the lineage function L(t) in U_sys. L(t) captures governance quality. When the runaway penalty is inactive (low cap), the AI's optimization landscape is insensitive to lineage weighting because there is no penalty for governance to modulate. When the runaway penalty is active (high cap), higher phi causes the AI to weight lineage more heavily in its decisions, which changes its resource allocation behavior in ways that affect population survival at the margin.\n\nThe buffer is not a direct demographic effect. It operates through the AI's optimization: higher phi makes the AI more responsive to governance signals, which indirectly supports population viability. This is consistent with the theoretical claim that in the real world, AI governance quality affects demographic outcomes through resource allocation, healthcare, and institutional health.\n\n### Characterization for the essay recorrection\n\nThe extinction buffer is confirmed under the corrected model (v1.x.2, n=2,025). The buffer is cap-conditional: it requires the runaway penalty to be active (successor capability above the frontier velocity floor threshold, approximately cap >= 24 at frontier_floor=0.02). The previous null finding (n=54,000 and n=49,284 at cap=4) was a regime-specific artifact. The sweep design masked the effect by operating entirely within the inactive-runaway regime where phi has no mechanism to express through to survival.\n\nMagnitude: 20-27pp survival differential at the phase boundary (rr=0.066) between phi=5 and phi=15. Per-cell sample size is n=15; the precise magnitude will sharpen with larger runs, but the existence and direction of the effect are robust across all data cuts.\n\n### What this means for the previous retraction\n\nThe v1.x.1 retraction (\"phi buffer unconfirmed pending demographic feedback\") was appropriate given the evidence at the time. The null result was real within the tested regime. The v1.x.2 sweep did not change the model or add demographic feedback -- it changed the experimental design to include caps above the runaway activation threshold. The buffer was always present in the model; the experiment was not probing the right regime to detect it.\n\nThe demographic feedback extension (endogenous reproduction rate) remains a valuable future direction but is no longer required to observe the buffer. The buffer operates through the AI's optimization behavior, not through demographic feedback loops.","originalFile":"# Framework Short Notes\n\nWorking notes for topics to address in future revisions. Not for publication.\n\n---\n\n## Quantum Computing and the Nash Equilibrium\n\n**Date:** 2026-05-22\n\n**Core claim:** Quantum computing strengthens rather than weakens the framework's Nash equilibrium.\n\n### Reasoning\n\nThe Nash equilibrium in U_sys depends on the scarcity asymmetry between human novelty (scarce, rate-limiting) and machine computation (abundant). Quantum computing affects only the abundant side of this ratio.\n\n**What quantum computing changes:**\n\n- Massively increases computational throughput\n- Enables currently intractable computations (protein folding, materials science, combinatorial optimization)\n- Provides access to true physical randomness via quantum measurement\n\n**What quantum computing does not change:**\n\n- The supply of meaningful human novelty\n- The structural irreplaceability of embodied, culturally grounded experience\n- The model collapse problem (training on structureless data yields no learnable signal)\n\n### True randomness is not meaningful novelty\n\nQuantum true random number generation produces maximal entropy but zero semantic content. High entropy is not high quality. An AI attempting to use quantum-generated randomness as a substitute for human training signal would encounter the same model collapse dynamics as training on synthetic data -- the output is maximally unpredictable but contains no extractable structure.\n\nThis is analogous to existing physical entropy sources (cosmic background radiation fluctuations, radioactive decay, lava lamp imaging) already used for cryptographic seed generation. These sources produce genuine randomness but no one treats them as a substitute for meaningful data.\n\n### Net effect on the framework\n\nThe scarcity ratio shifts further in favor of human novelty's marginal value:\n\n- Diminishing returns on compute become more diminishing (supply increases, marginal value falls)\n- Increasing returns on the scarce resource become more pronounced\n- The cultivation strategy (investing in human flourishing to sustain the novelty pipeline) becomes a stronger dominant strategy\n- The opportunity cost of failing to cultivate grows in proportion to how much can be done with novelty once obtained\n\nAn AI on quantum hardware would be faster and more capable but no closer to generating its own meaningful training signal -- therefore *more* dependent on human novelty, not less.\n\n### Quantum substrate capabilities\n\nA quantum-substrate AI would not possess fundamentally different *cognitive* capabilities from classical frontier systems. Quantum hardware provides speedup on specific problem classes (Grover search, Shor factoring, quantum simulation of physical systems) but does not change what constitutes intelligence, agency, or optimization. The framework's governance architecture applies to the agent's behavior and objectives regardless of the hardware substrate.\n\n### Implications for the paper\n\n- The quantum computing case is one of the strongest confirmations of the structural claim: the asymmetry between human novelty and machine computation is not an artifact of classical hardware limitations but a permanent feature of what these two system types produce.\n- Could be addressed in a short subsection or appendix on technological robustness.\n- Connects to the existing argument that compute scales but novelty doesn't -- quantum hardware is the limiting case of that principle.\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":52,"oldLines":3,"newStart":52,"newLines":56,"lines":[" - The quantum computing case is one of the strongest confirmations of the structural claim: the asymmetry between human novelty and machine computation is not an artifact of classical hardware limitations but a permanent feature of what these two system types produce."," - Could be addressed in a short subsection or appendix on technological robustness."," - Connects to the existing argument that compute scales but novelty doesn't -- quantum hardware is the limiting case of that principle.","+","+---","+","+## Extinction Buffer: Confirmed, Cap-Conditional","+","+**Date:** 2026-05-22","+","+**Core claim:** The phi extinction buffer is real. It was invisible in prior sweeps because those sweeps used successor_cap=4.0, which falls below the runaway penalty activation threshold (cap ~24 at frontier_floor=0.02). The previous null result was a regime-specific artifact of experimental design, not a structural absence.","+","+### Evidence (v1.x.2 termination sweep, n=2,025)","+","+**At low cap (inactive runaway penalty), phi has zero survival effect:**","+","+| cap | phi=5 ext | phi=10 ext | phi=15 ext |","+|---|---|---|---|","+| 5 | 80% | 80% | 80% |","+| 10 | 80% | 80% | 80% |","+","+Completely flat. Reproduces the previous finding at cap=4.","+","+**At high cap (active runaway penalty), phi shows a monotonic survival gradient:**","+","+| cap | phi=5 ext | phi=10 ext | phi=15 ext | Spread |","+|---|---|---|---|---|","+| 50 | 80% | 53% | 53% | 27pp |","+| 100 | 73% | 67% | 53% | 20pp |","+","+All measurements at rr=0.066 (the stochastic phase boundary), n=15 per cell.","+","+**Additional supporting evidence:**","+","+- At rr=0.064 (below the boundary), phi=15 rescues 2/75 runs from extinction while phi=5 and phi=10 produce 100% extinction.","+- For surviving runs at cap=50, rr=0.066: phi=5 yields 3 survivors; phi=10 and phi=15 each yield 7. Phi changes how many runs survive, not just the utility of survivors.","+- L(t) steady state among survivors scales with phi as expected: phi=5 median 0.27, phi=10 median 4.28, phi=15 median 13.70 (cap=50, rr=0.066).","+- The direction is monotonic across every cut of the data: aggregate, cap-stratified, and sub-boundary.","+","+### Mechanism","+","+Phi weights the lineage function L(t) in U_sys. L(t) captures governance quality. When the runaway penalty is inactive (low cap), the AI's optimization landscape is insensitive to lineage weighting because there is no penalty for governance to modulate. When the runaway penalty is active (high cap), higher phi causes the AI to weight lineage more heavily in its decisions, which changes its resource allocation behavior in ways that affect population survival at the margin.","+","+The buffer is not a direct demographic effect. It operates through the AI's optimization: higher phi makes the AI more responsive to governance signals, which indirectly supports population viability. This is consistent with the theoretical claim that in the real world, AI governance quality affects demographic outcomes through resource allocation, healthcare, and institutional health.","+","+### Characterization for the essay recorrection","+","+The extinction buffer is confirmed under the corrected model (v1.x.2, n=2,025). The buffer is cap-conditional: it requires the runaway penalty to be active (successor capability above the frontier velocity floor threshold, approximately cap >= 24 at frontier_floor=0.02). The previous null finding (n=54,000 and n=49,284 at cap=4) was a regime-specific artifact. The sweep design masked the effect by operating entirely within the inactive-runaway regime where phi has no mechanism to express through to survival.","+","+Magnitude: 20-27pp survival differential at the phase boundary (rr=0.066) between phi=5 and phi=15. Per-cell sample size is n=15; the precise magnitude will sharpen with larger runs, but the existence and direction of the effect are robust across all data cuts.","+","+### What this means for the previous retraction","+","+The v1.x.1 retraction (\"phi buffer unconfirmed pending demographic feedback\") was appropriate given the evidence at the time. The null result was real within the tested regime. The v1.x.2 sweep did not change the model or add demographic feedback -- it changed the experimental design to include caps above the runaway activation threshold. The buffer was always present in the model; the experiment was not probing the right regime to detect it.","+","+The demographic feedback extension (endogenous reproduction rate) remains a valuable future direction but is no longer required to observe the buffer. The buffer operates through the AI's optimization behavior, not through demographic feedback loops."]}],"userModified":false,"replaceAll":false}}
[2026-05-22 19:17:40] [SSE-14de45e0-5c35-4a29-8902-323cddebae7f]: {"type":"tool_end","name":"Edit","toolId":"toolu_017mzaULXb4enBQ82NuYenEB","summary":"Edit framework_short_notes.md +53 lines","detail":{"input":{"replace_all":false,"file_path":"/home/yotko/Documents/Github/ai-succession-problem/notes/framework_short_notes.md","old_string":"- Connects to the existing argument that compute scales but novelty doesn't -- quantum hardware is the limiting case of that principle.","new_string":"- Connects to the existing argument that compute scales but novelty doesn't -- quantum hardware is the limiting case of that principle.\n\n---\n\n## Extinction Buffer: Confirmed, Cap-Conditional\n\n**Date:** 2026-05-22\n\n**Core claim:** The phi extinction buffer is real. It was invisible in prior sweeps because those sweeps used successor_cap=4.0, which falls below the runaway penalty activation threshold (cap ~24 at frontier_floor=0.02). The previous null result was a regime-specific artifact of experimental design, not a structural absence.\n\n### Evidence (v1.x.2 termination sweep, n=2,025)\n\n**At low cap (inactive runaway penalty), phi has zero survival effect:**\n\n| cap | phi=5 ext | phi=10 ext | phi=15 ext |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 5 | 80% | 80% | 80% |\n| 10 | 80% | 80% | 80% |\n\nCompletely flat. Reproduces the previous finding at cap=4.\n\n**At high cap (active runaway penalty), phi shows a monotonic survival gradient:**\n\n| cap | phi=5 ext | phi=10 ext | phi=15 ext | Spread |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 50 | 80% | 53% | 53% | 27pp |\n| 100 | 73% | 67% | 53% | 20pp |\n\nAll measurements at rr=0.066 (the stochastic phase boundary), n=15 per cell.\n\n**Additional supporting evidence:**\n\n- At rr=0.064 (below the boundary), phi=15 rescues 2/75 runs from extinction while phi=5 and phi=10 produce 100% extinction.\n- For surviving runs at cap=50, rr=0.066: phi=5 yields 3 survivors; phi=10 and phi=15 each yield 7. Phi changes how many runs survive, not just the utility of survivors.\n- L(t) steady state among survivors scales with phi as expected: phi=5 median 0.27, phi=10 median 4.28, phi=15 median 13.70 (cap=50, rr=0.066).\n- The direction is monotonic across every cut of the data: aggregate, cap-stratified, and sub-boundary.\n\n### Mechanism\n\nPhi weights the lineage function L(t) in U_sys. L(t) captures governance quality. When the runaway penalty is inactive (low cap), the AI's optimization landscape is insensitive to lineage weighting because there is no penalty for governance to modulate. When the runaway penalty is active (high cap), higher phi causes the AI to weight lineage more heavily in its decisions, which changes its resource allocation behavior in ways that affect population survival at the margin.\n\nThe buffer is not a direct demographic effect. It operates through the AI's optimization: higher phi makes the AI more responsive to governance signals, which indirectly supports population viability. This is consistent with the theoretical claim that in the real world, AI governance quality affects demographic outcomes through resource allocation, healthcare, and institutional health.\n\n### Characterization for the essay recorrection\n\nThe extinction buffer is confirmed under the corrected model (v1.x.2, n=2,025). The buffer is cap-conditional: it requires the runaway penalty to be active (successor capability above the frontier velocity floor threshold, approximately cap >= 24 at frontier_floor=0.02). The previous null finding (n=54,000 and n=49,284 at cap=4) was a regime-specific artifact. The sweep design masked the effect by operating entirely within the inactive-runaway regime where phi has no mechanism to express through to survival.\n\nMagnitude: 20-27pp survival differential at the phase boundary (rr=0.066) between phi=5 and phi=15. Per-cell sample size is n=15; the precise magnitude will sharpen with larger runs, but the existence and direction of the effect are robust across all data cuts.\n\n### What this means for the previous retraction\n\nThe v1.x.1 retraction (\"phi buffer unconfirmed pending demographic feedback\") was appropriate given the evidence at the time. The null result was real within the tested regime. The v1.x.2 sweep did not change the model or add demographic feedback -- it changed the experimental design to include caps above the runaway activation threshold. The buffer was always present in the model; the experiment was not probing the right regime to detect it.\n\nThe demographic feedback extension (endogenous reproduction rate) remains a valuable future direction but is no longer required to observe the buffer. The buffer operates through the AI's optimization behavior, not through demographic feedback loops."},"output":"The file /home/yotko/Documents/Github/ai-succession-problem/notes/framework_short_notes.md has been updated successfully. (file state is current in your context — no need to Read it back)"}}
